### Visual Studio Code
You will need to install a code editor to build your prototype. We recommend installing the editor {{
    onsExternalLink({
        "url": 'https://code.visualstudio.com/download',
        "linkText": 'Visual Studio Code (VS Code)'
    })
}}

VS Code has a built-in terminal application (sometimes referred to as “using the command line”) which will allow you to run the prototype kit and commit and push your prototype to GitHub.

### Node.js
To check if you already have Node.js installed, open a new terminal (using the ‘Terminal’ menu in VS Code).

In the terminal window, enter:
{{ onsCodeHighlight({ "code": 'node --version' }) }}

If  a version of `v14.x.x` or higher is not displayed, or it says `command not found` or `Error 0x2 starting node.exe --version` then you will need to download the latest LTS (Long Term Support) version of {{
    onsExternalLink({
        "url": 'https://nodejs.org/en/',
        "linkText": 'Node.js'
    })
}}

Follow the installation instructions, using all the default options.

To check Node.js has installed correctly, restart your terminal application and enter the version command again.

### Yarn
Once you have Node.js installed, you can use it’s own package manager (npm) to install (or upgrade) Yarn.

In the terminal window, enter:
{{ onsCodeHighlight({ "code": 'npm install --global yarn' }) }}

To check Yarn has installed correctly, in your terminal window, enter:
{{ onsCodeHighlight({ "code": 'yarn --version' }) }}

The latest version should be displayed.

### Git
You will need to {{  onsExternalLink({
        "url": 'https://docs.github.com/en/get-started/quickstart/set-up-git',
        "linkText": 'download, install and set up Git'
    })
}} to track changes to your prototypes, and to push those commits to your GitHub repository to share online.

## 3. Download the prototype kit
To start building prototypes, you will need to download a local copy of your prototypes repository from GitHub.

Go to your prototypes repository in GitHub and select the button labelled “Code”.

With the “HTTPS” tab selected, copy the command line beneath to your clipboard.

+++
{% call onsCollapsible({
